===Etymology 1===
{{dercat|en|ine-pro}}
From {{inh|en|enm|marchen}}, from {{der|en|frm|marcher|t=to march, walk}}, from {{der|en|fro|marchier|t=to stride, to march, to trample}}, from {{der|en|frk|*markōn|t=to mark, mark out, to press with the foot}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*markōną|t=to mark}}. Akin to {{cog|ang|mearc}}, {{m|ang|ġemearc|t=mark, boundary}}. Compare {{m|en|mark}}, from {{inh|en|ang|mearcian}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}
[[File:Trooping the Colour form march past.JPG|thumb|Soldiers marching in the UK.]]

# {{senseid|en|formal, rhythmic way of walking}} A [[formal]], [[rhythmic]] way of [[walk]]ing, used especially by [[soldier]]s, by [[band]]s{{,}} and in [[ceremony|ceremonies]].
# {{senseid|en|journey made by marching style of walking}} A [[journey#Noun|journey]] so walked.
#: {{hyper|en|journey#Noun}}
# A [[political]] [[rally]] or [[parade]].
#: {{syn|en|protest|parade|rally}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2009-10-21|author=Dennis Hevesi|title=Jack Nelson, Journalist, Dies at 80|titleurl=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/22/business/media/22nelson.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|journal=w:The New York Times|accessdate=12 June 2014
|passage=Mr. Nelson covered the Selma-to-Montgomery freedom '''marches''', including Bloody Sunday, on March 7, 1965, when 600 marchers were attacked with billy clubs and tear gas.}}
# Any [[song]] in the [[genre]] of [[music]] written for marching (see [[w:March (music)|Wikipedia's article on this type of music]])
# Steady forward movement or progression.
#: {{syn|en|process|advancement|progression}}
#: {{ux|en|the '''march''' of time}}
# {{lb|en|[[euchre]]}} The feat of taking all the [[trick]]s of a [[hand]].

