===Etymology 2===
{{etymid|en|borderland}}
From {{inh|en|enm|marche|t=tract of land along a country's border}}, from {{der|en|fro|marche|t=boundary, frontier}}, from {{der|en|frk|*marku}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*markō}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*mórǵs|t=edge, boundary}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{senseid|en|border region}} {{lb|en|now|_|archaic|historical|often plural}} A border region, especially one originally set up to defend a [[boundary]].
#: {{syn|en|frontier|marchland|borderland}}
#: {{cot|en|county palatinate|county palatine}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1819|author=w:Lord Byron|title={{w|Don Juan (Byron)|Don Juan}}|section=IV|passage=Juan's companion was a Romagnole, / But bred within the '''March''' of old Ancona{{nb...}}.}}
# {{senseid|en|border region governed by a marquess}} {{lb|en|historical}} A region at a frontier governed by a [[marquess]].

=====Usage notes=====
Both ''march'' (noun) and ''[[land]]'' (noun) are predisposed [[idiom#Noun|idiomatically]] to be used in the plural such that a single region is conceived as a collection of smaller locales; thus, ''in the [[marches#Noun|marches]]'', ''in the [[borderlands]]'', and ''in the [[badlands]]'' are often not different [[Appendix:Glossary#denotation|denotationally]] from ''in the march'', ''in the [[borderland]]'', and ''in the [[badland]]'' although they are [[trivial]]ly different [[grammar#Noun|grammatically]] and [[Appendix:Glossary#connotation|connotatively]].

